<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-interpreting-ci" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Interpreting a confidence interval</title>
    <p>
        Confidence intervals are most useful when they accompany the results of a statistical analysis.
        In R-Instat, confidence intervals are calculated automatically for many statistical procedures,
        allowing you to focus on interpreting the results rather than performing the calculations manually.
        In this example, we estimate the relationship between the number of hours worked and the number of
        tasks completed using Pearson's correlation coefficient together with its 95% confidence interval.
    </p>
    <p>
        Begin by importing the <c>work</c> dataset from the <c>lsrdata</c> package. This dataset contains
        49 observations and includes the variables <c>hours</c>, <c>tasks</c>, <c>pay</c>,
        <c>day</c>, <c>weekday</c>, <c>week</c>, and <c>day.type</c>.
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Import the dataset using
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <c>File &gt; Import from Library &gt; Load from R</c>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Select <c>lsrdata</c> from the <c>From Package</c> drop-down list and choose the <c>work</c> dataset.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    To calculate the correlation together with its confidence interval, 
                    open the <term>Correlation</term> dialog from <c>Describe &gt; Two/Three Variables &gt; Correlations...</c>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Select the <term>Two Variables</term> tab and specify the following settings:
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                First Variable: <c>hours</c>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Second Variable: <c>tasks</c>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Method: <c>Pearson</c>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Confidence Interval: <c>0.95</c>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-correlation-ci-dialog">
        <caption>
            The Correlation dialog configured to calculate the Pearson correlation
            between <c>hours</c> and <c>tasks</c> together with a 95% confidence interval.
        </caption>
        <image source="images\estimation\correlation_ci_dialog.png"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Click <c>OK</c> to produce the output shown in
        <xref ref="fig-correlation-ci-output"/>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-correlation-ci-output">
        <caption>
            Output from the Correlation dialog showing the Pearson correlation coefficient
            and its 95% confidence interval.
        </caption>
        <image source="images\estimation\correlation_ci_output.png"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
        The output reports a Pearson correlation coefficient of
        <m>r = 0.8002</m>, indicating a strong positive linear relationship between the
        number of hours worked and the number of tasks completed. In general, employees
        who worked more hours also completed more tasks.
    </p>

    <p>
        More importantly for this section, the output also provides a 95% confidence
        interval for the population correlation, which ranges from approximately
        <m>0.6697</m> to <m>0.8827</m>. This interval represents a range of plausible
        values for the true correlation in the population. Since the entire interval is
        positive and lies well above zero, the data provide strong evidence of a positive
        association between the two variables.
    </p>

    <p>
        The width of the confidence interval also tells us about the precision of the
        estimate. A narrow interval indicates that the estimated correlation is relatively
        precise, whereas a wider interval would indicate greater uncertainty. Larger
        sample sizes generally produce narrower confidence intervals because they provide
        more reliable estimates of population parameters.
    </p>

    <p>
        When interpreting confidence intervals in R-Instat, it is good practice to
        consider both the point estimate and the confidence interval together. The point
        estimate summarises the observed relationship in the sample, while the confidence
        interval indicates the range of values that are consistent with the observed data.
        Reporting both provides a more complete understanding of the statistical results
        than reporting the point estimate alone.
    </p>
</subsection>